recently launched a new workshop titled \"FP: From Zero to Monad\".\n\nThe goal of the workshop is to cover (not exhaustively, but sufficiently) the basic tenets of FP -- like pure functions, closure, currying, etc -- in a build-up to finally understanding and learning to practically use monads (and related category theory patterns) in our applications.\n\nWhile I use JS for this workshop -- and show off some JS libraries to aid in doing it -- the concepts are transferable to other languages, especially to FP-oriented ones (Scala, Clojure, Haskell, F#, OCAML, etc).\n\n----\n\nI know FP is a bit of a \"second class citizen\" in most people's view. It's like \"ah, yeah, that sounds nice, but...\" kind of thing. The big concern is usually the barrier to entry of learning for newer devs, as well as the \"switching cost\" to refactor code bases using such different techniques.\n\nBut even as FP is viewed that way, the topic of monads (and related topics) is even MORE of a niche topic, something usually only the most dedicated of FP folks push into.\n\nNevertheless, I've become more and more convinced that this mindset is what we're missing -- and more importantly, what all the framework designs are missing -- and that we could significantly improve how we build our apps if we pushed into this unfamiliar territory. That instead of monads being an \"advanced only\" type of topic, it should actually be the main focus of WHY you should get into FP in the first place!\n\nI believe the \"pain\" of pushing ourselves (and others on the team) to lean into FP and monads is more than worth it. But I'm not sure if others would be willing to set aside their skepticism and give it a try?\n\nSo... I'm curious for my followers here... if you had a chance to take this workshop, do you think you would do recently launched a new workshop titled \"FP: From Zero to Monad\".\n\nThe goal of the workshop is to cover (not exhaustively, but sufficiently) the basic tenets of FP -- like pure functions, closure, currying, etc -- in a build-up to finally understanding and learning to practically use monads (and related category theory patterns) in our applications.\n\nWhile I use JS for this workshop -- and show off some JS libraries to aid in doing it -- the concepts are transferable to other languages, especially to FP-oriented ones (Scala, Clojure, Haskell, F#, OCAML, etc).\n\n----\n\nI know FP is a bit of a \"second class citizen\" in most people's view. It's like \"ah, yeah, that sounds nice, but...\" kind of thing. The big concern is usually the barrier to entry of learning for newer devs, as well as the \"switching cost\" to refactor code bases using such different techniques.\n\nBut even as FP is viewed that way, the topic of monads (and related topics) is even MORE of a niche topic, something usually only the most dedicated of FP folks push into.\n\nNevertheless, I've become more and more convinced that this mindset is what we're missing -- and more importantly, what all the framework designs are missing -- and that we could significantly improve how we build our apps if we pushed into this unfamiliar territory. That instead of monads being an \"advanced only\" type of topic, it should actually be the main focus of WHY you should get into FP in the first place!\n\nI believe the \"pain\" of pushing ourselves (and others on the team) to lean into FP and monads is more than worth it. But I'm not sure if others would be willing to set aside their skepticism and give it a try?\n\nSo... I'm curious for my followers here... if you had a chance to take this workshop, do you think you would do
